\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Evidence gap map: bias--mitigation intersections in histopathology AI fairness research. Each cell records the number of studies explicitly testing the bias--mitigation pair, colour-coded by qualitative effectiveness grade (strong, moderate, mixed, emerging, failed). Cells marked `--' indicate pairings that are methodologically inapplicable or untested in the corpus. Rows are ordered by study count (technical/domain-shift: 8 studies; demographic: 5 studies); columns by mitigation stage (pre-processing to post-processing). The map reveals that clinically highest-risk bias categories (demographic, representation) are the most sparsely tested, while technically convenient categories attract disproportionate effort.}}{12}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:evidence_gap}{{4}{12}{Evidence gap map: bias--mitigation intersections in histopathology AI fairness research. Each cell records the number of studies explicitly testing the bias--mitigation pair, colour-coded by qualitative effectiveness grade (strong, moderate, mixed, emerging, failed). Cells marked `--' indicate pairings that are methodologically inapplicable or untested in the corpus. Rows are ordered by study count (technical/domain-shift: 8 studies; demographic: 5 studies); columns by mitigation stage (pre-processing to post-processing). The map reveals that clinically highest-risk bias categories (demographic, representation) are the most sparsely tested, while technically convenient categories attract disproportionate effort}{figure.4}{}}
